So, a valuable late contribution from Bollinger, who helped Hussey add 31 for the last wicket. Will 253 be a par score? It might well be, if Australia use the conditions with anything like the same skill. Don't go away, unless it's to boil the kettle. We're all for that sort of behaviour.

"Andrew!" exclaims Ali Shah. "You being unfair! It cant be Sydney! Kamran didnt drop any and Afridi is not as defensive as Yousuf." Very fair point, Ali, Pakistan played mighty well in this first innings. But Hussey's half-century could still prove crucial.

"What is the weather like today?," asks Iain who is stuck in rainy Scotland. "A bowling day or a batting day?" Well, it's brighter than yesterday but I reckon there'll be movement for the Aussie new-ball attack as well.

A real test for a young Pakistan batting line-up, which features two debutants in Umar Amin and Azhar Ali - about whom Andy Zaltzman has written in his latest Confectionary Stall blog. Read it at once, I implore you.

That's it. Afridi wanted to persist with Asif so the umpires decide they've seen enough and call the players off for bad light. Fascinating opening day, Pakistan have got themselves into a very good position but still need to finish the innings off tomorrow.

Aamer started the day well for Pakistan, removing Watson and Ponting before Clarke and Katich fought back strongly. Then, in a few balls either side of tea, Asif changed the game by dismissing Clarke, Katich and North in a flash. It opened the door for Kaneria to take a couple and Gul one so all that stands in Pakistan's way now is Hussey. But we've said that before.

It would be very surprising if we get any more action today but when we hear for sure, so will you. Right, that is indeed stumps.

Plenty to point you to - a good place to start would be Andrew Miller's bulletin, which will be ready shortly. For those who think in pictures we have a beautiful gallery of the day's best action and any Pakistan fans thinking ahead might also want to check out this video of Kevin Pietersen giving his thoughts on the upcoming series.

Anyway, that's all from me, Sahil Dutta, and from Andrew McGlashan, I hope you'll join us tomorrow morning for what should be an intriguing second day.
